, R. MARX, in Coll. LACKERBECK”.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="19.[192,1441,1250,1915]" pageId="19" pageNumber="18">
In 1998 the third edition of the International Code of Zoological Nomenclature (
<bibRefCitation author="ICZN &amp; International Commission of Zoological Nomenclature" box="[1205,1344,1410,1434]" pageId="19" pageNumber="18" refId="ref18875" refString="ICZN [International Commission of Zoological Nomenclature]. 1985. International Code of Zoological Nomenclature. Third Edition. International Trust for Zoological Nomenclature, in association with the British Museum (Natural History); London. 338 p." type="book" year="1985">ICZN 1985</bibRefCitation>
), was in force. According to the Recommendation 72A of this edition: “The term ‘allotype’ may be used to designate among 
<typeStatus box="[345,466,1475,1499]" pageId="19" pageNumber="18">paratypes</typeStatus>
a specimen of opposite sex to the 
<typeStatus box="[886,996,1474,1498]" pageId="19" pageNumber="18">holotype</typeStatus>
. Authors are recommended to avoid using the term ‘allotype’ for specimens other than 
<typeStatus box="[798,924,1506,1530]" pageId="19" pageNumber="18">paratypes</typeStatus>
”. Evidently a recommendation is not a law, and so, many authors at that time designated 
<typeStatus box="[737,846,1538,1562]" pageId="19" pageNumber="18">allotypes</typeStatus>
that did not belong to the type series. Thus, when 
<bibRefCitation author="Lackerbeck, K." box="[192,415,1570,1594]" pageId="19" pageNumber="18" pagination="517 - 524" refId="ref19059" refString="Lackerbeck, K. 1998. Neue und wenig bekannte Prioninae (Coleoptera, Cerambycidae). Entomofauna Zeitschrift fur Entomologie 19 (32): 517 - 524." type="journal article" year="1998">Lackerbeck (1998)</bibRefCitation>
designated a female from his private collection as 
<typeStatus box="[1009,1109,1570,1594]" pageId="19" pageNumber="18">allotype</typeStatus>
, he did not violate the Code. However, he violated the Code when he considered this 
<typeStatus box="[900,998,1602,1626]" pageId="19" pageNumber="18">allotype</typeStatus>
as a 
<typeStatus box="[1070,1183,1603,1627]" pageId="19" pageNumber="18">paratype</typeStatus>
. The specimen from Lackerbeck’s Collection is not a type, and does not have any special value.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="19.[192,1441,1250,1915]" pageId="19" pageNumber="18">
The males of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Quentin and Villiers" authorityYear="1983" box="[403,541,1666,1690]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Psalidognathus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="19" pageNumber="18" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rufescens">
<emphasis box="[403,541,1666,1690]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="18">P. rufescens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
deposited at MZSP and ZKCO are slimmer than the 
<typeStatus box="[1183,1293,1666,1690]" pageId="19" pageNumber="18">holotype</typeStatus>
. The female figured in 
<bibRefCitation author="Lackerbeck, K." box="[324,554,1698,1722]" pageId="19" pageNumber="18" pagination="517 - 524" refId="ref19059" refString="Lackerbeck, K. 1998. Neue und wenig bekannte Prioninae (Coleoptera, Cerambycidae). Entomofauna Zeitschrift fur Entomologie 19 (32): 517 - 524." type="journal article" year="1998">Lackerbeck (1998)</bibRefCitation>
is wider than we expected, after examining the males. However, when compared with the male 
<typeStatus box="[488,596,1730,1754]" pageId="19" pageNumber="18">holotype</typeStatus>
, the body is not disproportionate, although the elytra is laterally more rounded than females of other species. This is particularly important, because the males of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Quentin and Villiers" authorityYear="1983" box="[1303,1441,1762,1786]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Psalidognathus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="19" pageNumber="18" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rufescens">
<emphasis box="[1303,1441,1762,1786]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="18">P. rufescens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
have the elytra with sides more parallel than other species of 
<taxonomicName box="[936,1127,1794,1818]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Psalidognathus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="19" pageNumber="18" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[936,1127,1794,1818]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="18">Psalidognathus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="19.[192,1441,1250,1915]" lastBlockId="20.[192,1441,194,794]" lastPageId="20" lastPageNumber="19" pageId="19" pageNumber="18">
<bibRefCitation author="Quentin, R. M. &amp; A. Villiers" box="[240,580,1826,1850]" pageId="19" pageNumber="18" pagination="441 - 446" refId="ref19641" refString="Quentin, R. M., and A. Villiers. 1983. Note sur les Psalidognathus Gray. Description de quatre formes nouvelles; designation d'un neotype et de lectotypes (Col., Cerambycidae, Prioninae). Annales de la Societe Entomologique de France (n. s.) 19 (4): 441 - 446." type="journal article" year="1983">Quentin and Villiers (1983)</bibRefCitation>
recorded (translation): “distance between upper ocular lobes equal to about one third of a lobe seen from above.” However, their 
<figureCitation box="[904,1006,1858,1882]" captionStart="Figure 1-7" captionStartId="25.[192,275,1751,1773]" captionTargetBox="[232,1426,213,1721]" captionTargetId="figure-623@25.[760,842,962,1003]" captionTargetPageId="25" captionText="Figure 1-7. Psalidognathus thomsoni. 1) Lectotype male, dorsal habitus. 2) Lectotype male, head and pronotum. 3) Lectotype male, partial lateral view. 4) Male, dorsal habitus. 5) Male, head showing cephalic carinae. 6) Female, dorsal habitus. 7) Lectotype, labels. Photos 1, 2, 3, and 7 by Eugenio Nearns." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5174597" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5174597/files/figure.png" pageId="19" pageNumber="18">Figure 4</figureCitation>
shows that this distance is approximately equal to a lobe. Their drawing (
<figureCitation box="[658,763,1890,1914]" captionStart="Figure 1-7" captionStartId="25.[192,275,1751,1773]" captionTargetBox="[232,1426,213,1721]" captionTargetId="figure-623@25.[760,842,962,1003]" captionTargetPageId="25" captionText="Figure 1-7. Psalidognathus thomsoni. 1) Lectotype male, dorsal habitus. 2) Lectotype male, head and pronotum. 3) Lectotype male, partial lateral view. 4) Male, dorsal habitus. 5) Male, head showing cephalic carinae. 6) Female, dorsal habitus. 7) Lectotype, labels. Photos 1, 2, 3, and 7 by Eugenio Nearns." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5174597" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5174597/files/figure.png" pageId="19" pageNumber="18">Figure 4</figureCitation>
) does not agree with the 
<typeStatus box="[1063,1169,1890,1914]" pageId="19" pageNumber="18">holotype</typeStatus>
(
<figureCitation box="[1183,1270,1890,1914]" captionStart="Figure 25-30" captionStartId="29.[192,275,1742,1764]" captionTargetBox="[232,1406,232,1714]" captionTargetPageId="29" captionText="Figure 25-30. Dorsal habitus. 25) Psalidognathus rufescens, holotype male. 26) P. rufescens, female. 27) P. cerberus sp. nov., holotype male. 28) P. cerberus sp. nov., paratype female. 29) P. cerberus sp. nov., paratype male. 30) P. cerberus sp. nov., paratype male, head. Photos 25 and 26 by Ivo Jeniš." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5174605" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5174605/files/figure.png" pageId="19" pageNumber="18">Fig. 25</figureCitation>
), in which the distance between upper ocular lobes is slightly less than the width of a lobe. Additionally, the apex of the upper ocular lobe is distinctly narrower in the 
<typeStatus box="[758,864,226,250]" pageId="20" pageNumber="19">holotype</typeStatus>
than in 
<figureCitation box="[964,1071,226,250]" captionStart="Figure 1-7" captionStartId="25.[192,275,1751,1773]" captionTargetBox="[232,1426,213,1721]" captionTargetId="figure-623@25.[760,842,962,1003]" captionTargetPageId="25" captionText="Figure 1-7. Psalidognathus thomsoni. 1) Lectotype male, dorsal habitus. 2) Lectotype male, head and pronotum. 3) Lectotype male, partial lateral view. 4) Male, dorsal habitus. 5) Male, head showing cephalic carinae. 6) Female, dorsal habitus. 7) Lectotype, labels. Photos 1, 2, 3, and 7 by Eugenio Nearns." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5174597" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5174597/files/figure.png" pageId="20" pageNumber="19">Figure 4</figureCitation>
. The shape and distance of the upper ocular lobe in 
<bibRefCitation author="Quentin, R. M. &amp; A. Villiers" box="[447,786,258,282]" pageId="20" pageNumber="19" pagination="441 - 446" refId="ref19641" refString="Quentin, R. M., and A. Villiers. 1983. Note sur les Psalidognathus Gray. Description de quatre formes nouvelles; designation d'un neotype et de lectotypes (Col., Cerambycidae, Prioninae). Annales de la Societe Entomologique de France (n. s.) 19 (4): 441 - 446." type="journal article" year="1983">Quentin and Villiers (1983)</bibRefCitation>
<figureCitation box="[793,897,258,282]" captionStart="Figure 1-7" captionStartId="25.[192,275,1751,1773]" captionTargetBox="[232,1426,213,1721]" captionTargetId="figure-623@25.[760,842,962,1003]" captionTargetPageId="25" captionText="Figure 1-7. Psalidognathus thomsoni. 1) Lectotype male, dorsal habitus. 2) Lectotype male, head and pronotum. 3) Lectotype male, partial lateral view. 4) Male, dorsal habitus. 5) Male, head showing cephalic carinae. 6) Female, dorsal habitus. 7) Lectotype, labels. Photos 1, 2, 3, and 7 by Eugenio Nearns." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5174597" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5174597/files/figure.png" pageId="20" pageNumber="19">Figure 4</figureCitation>
agrees perfectly with the males deposited at MZSP and ZKCO.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="20.[192,1441,194,794]" pageId="20" pageNumber="19">
Regarding the integument, 
<bibRefCitation author="Quentin, R. M. &amp; A. Villiers" box="[571,902,322,346]" pageId="20" pageNumber="19" pagination="441 - 446" refId="ref19641" refString="Quentin, R. M., and A. Villiers. 1983. Note sur les Psalidognathus Gray. Description de quatre formes nouvelles; designation d'un neotype et de lectotypes (Col., Cerambycidae, Prioninae). Annales de la Societe Entomologique de France (n. s.) 19 (4): 441 - 446." type="journal article" year="1983">Quentin and Villiers (1983)</bibRefCitation>
wrote (translation): “Entirely reddish, head, antennae and legs darker.” Nevertheless, 
<bibRefCitation author="Lackerbeck, K." box="[708,937,354,378]" pageId="20" pageNumber="19" pagination="517 - 524" refId="ref19059" refString="Lackerbeck, K. 1998. Neue und wenig bekannte Prioninae (Coleoptera, Cerambycidae). Entomofauna Zeitschrift fur Entomologie 19 (32): 517 - 524." type="journal article" year="1998">Lackerbeck (1998)</bibRefCitation>
pointed out (translation): “Black, elytra reddish.” The male deposited at ZKCO has the prothorax and legs more reddish than the 
<typeStatus box="[1281,1387,386,410]" pageId="20" pageNumber="19">holotype</typeStatus>
and the specimen deposited at MZSP, in which they are dark brown. Thus, it appears that the color can be darker or lighter.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="20.[192,1441,194,794]" pageId="20" pageNumber="19">
<bibRefCitation author="Lackerbeck, K." box="[240,465,482,506]" pageId="20" pageNumber="19" pagination="517 - 524" refId="ref19059" refString="Lackerbeck, K. 1998. Neue und wenig bekannte Prioninae (Coleoptera, Cerambycidae). Entomofauna Zeitschrift fur Entomologie 19 (32): 517 - 524." type="journal article" year="1998">Lackerbeck (1998)</bibRefCitation>
also wrote (translation): “By the little bulge formed on the vertex and sides of the head can easily be differentiated from all other 
<taxonomicName box="[761,952,514,538]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Psalidognathus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="20" pageNumber="19" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[761,952,514,538]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="19">Psalidognathus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, except 
<taxonomicName authority="REICHE, 1840" authorityName="Reiche" authorityYear="1840" box="[1048,1425,514,538]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Psalidognathus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="20" pageNumber="12" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="erythrocerus">
<emphasis box="[1048,1232,514,538]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="19">P. Erythrocerus</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Reiche, L." box="[1236,1425,514,538]" pageId="20" pageNumber="19" pagination="358" refId="ref19704" refString="Reiche, L. 1840. Nouvelle espece du genre Psalidognathus de M. Gray. Revue de Zoologie 1840: 358." type="journal article" year="1840">REICHE, 1840</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
.” This is not true. Males of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Reiche" authorityYear="1840" box="[522,701,546,570]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Psalidognathus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="20" pageNumber="19" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="erythrocerus">
<emphasis box="[522,701,546,570]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="19">P. erythrocerus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
have a very distinct tubercle on the sides of the head, and females of many species of 
<taxonomicName box="[536,728,578,602]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Psalidognathus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="20" pageNumber="19" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[536,728,578,602]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="19">Psalidognathus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
have lateral tubercles exactly like those of Lackerbeck’s female (sometimes absent). Regarding the cephalic carinae, they are similar to those of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lameere" authorityYear="1885" box="[1231,1366,610,634]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Psalidognathus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="20" pageNumber="19" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="thomsoni">
<emphasis box="[1231,1366,610,634]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="19">P. thomsoni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(male and female), to those of species in the “ 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Gray" authorityYear="1831" box="[670,763,642,666]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Psalidognathus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="20" pageNumber="19" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="friendii">
<emphasis box="[670,763,642,666]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="19">friendii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
” group, and to those of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Reiche" authorityYear="1840" box="[1058,1235,642,666]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Psalidognathus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="20" pageNumber="19" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="erythrocerus">
<emphasis box="[1058,1235,642,666]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="19">P. erythrocerus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
females.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="20.[192,1441,194,794]" pageId="20" pageNumber="19">
Based on the features observed by us, and comparing the female in 
<bibRefCitation author="Lackerbeck, K." box="[1050,1276,674,698]" pageId="20" pageNumber="19" pagination="517 - 524" refId="ref19059" refString="Lackerbeck, K. 1998. Neue und wenig bekannte Prioninae (Coleoptera, Cerambycidae). Entomofauna Zeitschrift fur Entomologie 19 (32): 517 - 524." type="journal article" year="1998">Lackerbeck (1998)</bibRefCitation>
with another deposited at MNHN (
<figureCitation box="[454,540,706,730]" captionStart="Figure 25-30" captionStartId="29.[192,275,1742,1764]" captionTargetBox="[232,1406,232,1714]" captionTargetPageId="29" captionText="Figure 25-30. Dorsal habitus. 25) Psalidognathus rufescens, holotype male. 26) P. rufescens, female. 27) P. cerberus sp. nov., holotype male. 28) P. cerberus sp. nov., paratype female. 29) P. cerberus sp. nov., paratype male. 30) P. cerberus sp. nov., paratype male, head. Photos 25 and 26 by Ivo Jeniš." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5174605" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5174605/files/figure.png" pageId="20" pageNumber="19">Fig. 26</figureCitation>
) we conclude that both are really 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Quentin and Villiers" authorityYear="1983" box="[956,1094,706,730]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Psalidognathus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="20" pageNumber="19" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rufescens">
<emphasis box="[956,1094,706,730]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="19">P. rufescens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. But it is interesting to note that the female deposited at MNHN has the apical third of the elytral narrower than the females in 
<bibRefCitation author="Lackerbeck, K." box="[192,421,770,794]" pageId="20" pageNumber="19" pagination="517 - 524" refId="ref19059" refString="Lackerbeck, K. 1998. Neue und wenig bekannte Prioninae (Coleoptera, Cerambycidae). Entomofauna Zeitschrift fur Entomologie 19 (32): 517 - 524." type="journal article" year="1998">Lackerbeck (1998)</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
